# TypeScript (React)

## Coding standards

- Prefer functional components over class components.
- Use TypeScript interfaces for props and state; do not add PropTypes when types are present.
- Use `useState` and `useEffect` for state and side effects; keep `useEffect` dependency arrays accurate.
- Extract reusable logic into custom hooks (e.g. debouncing, list totals).
- Use `React.memo` only when profiling shows a measurable benefit.
- Strict TypeScript is enabled — avoid `any` and unused locals/parameters.

## Folder structure

```
src/
  components/
  constants/
  contexts/
  hooks/
  pages/
  utils/
  api/
  App.tsx
```

## Performance

- Lazy-load route-level pages with `React.lazy` and `Suspense` when bundle size matters.
- Debounce search/filter inputs that trigger API calls.
- Use React Query `placeholderData` / `keepPreviousData` thoughtfully for pagination vs filter changes.

## Error handling

- Wrap async mutations in `try/catch` when the caller must set UI error state.
- Surface API errors via `ApiError` messages where the page already has error UI.

## Conventions

- Use `.tsx` for files containing JSX.
- Shared UI actions (e.g. delete document) belong in `src/components/`.
- Shared magic numbers and status strings belong in `src/constants/globals.ts`.
- Match existing naming: Catalan UI copy, `@/` path aliases, `btn` / `field` CSS classes.

## Out of scope unless requested

- Mandatory 80% test coverage or snapshot tests for every component.
- `React.FC` as a required pattern.
- Per-directory bilingual README files.
